<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910114-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910114-0114.</DOCID><HL>   Chicago Merc Increases   Margin for Some Futures</HL><DATE>01/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><LP>   CHICAGO -- The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, citing thecrisis in the Mideast, is increasing the amount of money, ormargin, required by traders to establish and maintain tradingpositions in certain financial futures contracts.   The Merc said the increases are being made &quot;in light ofthe potential for market volatility if hostilities commencein the Middle East.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Effective today, the Merc increased to $10,000 a contractfrom $8,000 the amount of margin required of tradersinitiating or maintaining a position in Standard andamp; Poor's500-stock index futures used to hedge against losses onholdings in related markets. A similar increase takes effectfor speculators maintaining positions in the Sandamp;P 500 futurescontract. The initial speculative margin for stock-indexfutures remains unchanged at $22,000 a contract.   As of tomorrow, margins for hedge traders and speculatorsare being increased by varying amounts for Eurodollarfutures, one-month Libor futures and Treasury bill futures.The Libor is the London interbank offered rate, the interestrate that the most credit-worthy international banks dealingin Eurodollars charge each other for large loans. Among theMerc's foreign currency futures, margin increases take effecttomorrow for British pound, German mark and Swiss francfutures.</TEXT></DOC>